There is *a surprising amount of detail* to fashion design, and running a legit fashion brand (i.e. not merch & not bandwagon streetwear)
At the designer levels (ie McQueen/Balmain/etc), running a brand is about as difficult as running a hardware startup
AI is good for the superficial - it can generate images that kinda sorta convey *some* details...
...but again until AGI, those details have to be interpreted by a designer/pattern maker, and that’s where rubber meets road
Having worked w/designers everyday for ~3 years (streetwear all the way up to haute couture), there are four things that separate the men from the boys
1) Material Quality, 2) Color/dye quality, 3) trims, and 4) fit
To create something amazing, a designer/house has to have very strong opinions on *each of those*

AI can kinda generate fuzzy outlines that *may* give a designer inspo, but until there’s an AI that’s been trained on *actual fashion data* - material composition/drape/feel, print marker creation & grading of assets, creative and opinionated use of trims, and the can of geometric worms that is pattern among (which requires a lot of subjective decisions about how to translate between 2D/3D geo), a designer’s eye will always be necessary

AI can I guess work for merch, since that’s basically sublimation/screenprinting a PNG/TIFF onto a pre-made silhouette...but that’s just GPT-3 on a Hanes T, not the identity/wholistic POV we seek from fashion.
And then actually *manufacturing* a line of custom clothes is where you really sell your soul...the lead times & logistical hurdles are the stuff of nightmares...

@Saad Sure, those applications can and do work! But I think they’re a really long way away from the  “AI will eat fashion” discourse going on

Fit is definitely the best application rn - and companies like Perfitly and Clo3d are already using machine vision and garment simulation (respectively) to map your avatar to garments in 3D. But it doesn’t really solve much in the current industry model - the tailoring idea has a lot of pitfalls even if you manage to scale it (+3/4 day lead times & higher costs for consumers, skilled-enough tailors aren’t that plentiful). You really have to have on-demand garment manufacturing to make personalized fit work.
But I’m _extremely_ bearish on any sort of personal stylist app achieving wide adoption/becoming the norm.

I think this is indicative of a huge cultural blind spot in tech. Style is not and will never be derived from utility. Techies take it as a given that value can only be created as overflow from the unreasonable effectiveness of systems. This is a really impoverished worldview.

An AI generating recommendations is about utility (you don’t have to pay $2k for a session w/ a real personal stylist, don’t have to invest time in gaining taste yourself). So “taste at scale” or w/e. But _by definition_ style/taste/auteurism cannot scale, not in a rational, systematic way.

Recommendation AIs are contradictory in that they’re sold as machines that can understand who we “really” are, our true tastes and our true aesthetic, and generate recs based of that identity. Yet we seek them out at precisely the moment we feel we _aren’t_ embodying enough of our true selves! (Why would we need recs in the first place if we were confident in our tastes?)

AI recs are generated from the person who is seeking them. For SV folks, _this is seen as a success._ But that’s a not-even-wrong definition of success. It’s sort of like in quant finance how there’s a whole class of errors where the ML model fails to see that a price is already a prediction.

Taste is discontinuity. It’s not a function of knowability - you can’t just throw someone’s past preferences into a mushy pile of linear algebra and stir. That will just give you more mush. Taste is the opposite of that - it’s magical because of how sharply it refutes what came before it, while at the same time being blinding in its inevitability.

@Michael RyeBread I actually see it as a sort of conformity tax.
Following "conspicuous consumption is consumption for the purpose of increasing prestige," I hear, very loudly, an implicit "in the most hassle-free manner available."

People of means almost always cave to signaling pressures - yes, it would be ideal if they could channel their wealth into moonshot or charitable projects, and be ambitious Elon Musk-types with their fortunes.
But most can't, and most aren't. They can't handle the illegibility of those routes, doubly so for the nouveau riche. The conformity tax gets levied on them, and they cough up.

Louis Vuitton, Harvard, Design Within Reach et al. are running something akin to a protection racket for legible prestige. The most legible means of increasing one's status are always the costliest, from a monetary perspective. Because when price is the only differentiator, the number quickly becomes more and more arbitrary.

This is why introducing something like a luxury tax would be meaningless (modulo whatever good that revenue could contribute towards) - the Gucci belt, or Eames chair, or Steinway, is itself 100% pure taxation already.

So the arms-race dynamics CC is a market failure, but it's an increasingly strong signal that individuality, done right, will have outsized leverage. Like a pile of $20 bills accumulating on the floor of Grand Central.

Sooner or later, the pressure valve on the prestige racket will burst, and whoever was smart/creative enough to explore new stylistic territory will be best positioned stake their claim in the ensuing gold rush of new status-symbol legibleization (emergence of streetwear is a prime example of this).
Call it the Efficient Snowflake Hypothesis - I believe style/taste to be orthogonal to artistry/creation, and relies on ESH as an incentive rather than mostly intrinsic motivation like the latter.

What appeals to me about zero inventory is that it is orthogonal to efforts at coordination and activism  (or failures thereof).

All things considered, I fall on the side of trying to eliminate tradeoffs rather than navigate them.
